Modify App Behavior Using Frida's CLI Toolkit
Objectives
By the end of this lab, students will be able to:

Install and configure Frida's command-line toolkit for mobile application testing
Hook methods in Android applications to intercept and modify runtime behavior
Identify common mobile application security vulnerabilities using dynamic analysis
Create Frida scripts to automate penetration testing workflows
Use Python to orchestrate automated security testing campaigns
Prerequisites
Before starting this lab, students should have:

Basic Linux command line proficiency
Understanding of Android application architecture and components
Fundamental JavaScript syntax knowledge
Basic Python programming skills
Familiarity with mobile application security concepts
Lab Environment
Your cloud environment includes:

Ubuntu 20.04 LTS with Frida toolkit pre-installed
Android Debug Bridge (ADB) configured
Android emulator with vulnerable test application (InsecureBankv2)
Python 3.8+ with Frida bindings
All necessary dependencies and tools
Task 1: Configure Frida and Hook Application Methods
Step 1: Verify Environment and Start Target Application
Check that Frida is properly installed and launch the test environment:

# Verify Frida installation
frida --version
python3 -c "import frida; print(frida.__version__)"

# Start Android emulator
emulator -avd test_device -no-snapshot-load &
sleep 120

# Verify device connection
adb devices

# Install and launch vulnerable application
cd ~/Downloads
adb install InsecureBankv2.apk
adb shell am start -n com.android.insecurebankv2/.PostLogin

# Confirm application is running
frida-ps -U | grep insecurebank
